  1. Tokenize the abstracts into bigrams. Find the 10 most common bigrams and visualize them.
top10_bigrams <- pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(bigram, abstract, token = "ngrams", n = 2) %>%
  separate(bigram, into = c("w1", "w2"), sep = " ", remove = FALSE) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = c("w1" = "word")) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = c("w2" = "word")) %>%
  unite(bigram, w1, w2, sep = " ", remove = TRUE) %>%
  count(bigram, sort = TRUE) %>%
  top_n(10, n)  

top10_bigrams %>%
  rename(Bigram = bigram, Count = n) %>%
  kbl(caption = "Top 10 Most Frequent Bigrams") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

  1. Calculate the TF-IDF value for each word-search term combination (here you want the search term to be the âdocumentâ). What are the 5 tokens from each search term with the highest TF-IDF value? How are the results different from the answers you got in Question 1?
term_word_counts <- pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") %>%
  filter(!str_detect(word, "^[0-9]+$")) %>%
  count(term, word, name = "n", sort = TRUE)

tfidf_tbl <- term_word_counts %>%
  bind_tf_idf(word, term, n) %>%       
  arrange(term, desc(tf_idf))

# Top 5 TF-IDF tokens per term
top5_tfidf <- tfidf_tbl %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  slice_max(tf_idf, n = 5, with_ties = FALSE) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  select(term, word, n, tf, idf, tf_idf)

top5_tfidf %>%
  rename(Term = term, Token = word, Count = n, TF = tf, IDF = idf, `TF-IDF` = tf_idf) %>%
  kbl(caption = "Top 5 tokens per search term by TF-IDF") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)

Sentiment Analysis

  1. Perform a sentiment analysis using the NRC lexicon. What is the most common sentiment for each search term? What if you remove "positive" and "negative" from the list?
# Sentiments
sent_counts <- pubmed %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  anti_join(tidytext::stop_words, by = "word") %>%
  filter(!str_detect(word, "^[0-9]+$")) %>%
  inner_join(tidytext::get_sentiments("nrc"), by = "word") %>%
  count(term, sentiment, name = "n", sort = TRUE)

# Most common sentiment per term 
top_sent <- sent_counts %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 1, with_ties = TRUE) %>%
  ungroup()

top_sent %>%
  rename(Term = term, Sentiment = sentiment, Count = n) %>%
  kbl(caption = "Most common NRC sentiment per search term") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)
Most common NRC sentiment per search term
Term Sentiment Count
covid positive 9254
cystic fibrosis positive 2564
meningitis negative 1959
preeclampsia positive 7603
prostate cancer negative 8799 
# Repeat excluding "positive" and "negative"
top_sent_no_pn <- sent_counts %>%
  filter(!sentiment %in% c("positive", "negative")) %>%
  group_by(term) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 1, with_ties = TRUE) %>%
  ungroup()

top_sent_no_pn %>%
  rename(Term = term, Sentiment = sentiment, Count = n) %>%
  kbl(caption = "Most common NRC sentiment per search term excluding 'positive' and 'negative'") %>%
  kable_styling(full_width = FALSE)
Most common NRC sentiment per search term excluding 'positive' and 'negative'
Term Sentiment Count
covid fear 7373
cystic fibrosis disgust 1714
meningitis fear 1371
preeclampsia anticipation 4555
prostate cancer fear 8039

Negative and positive connotations may not reflect the true sentiments in the abstract as it is very arbitrary what counts as ânegativeâ and âpositiveâ, so more detailed information was needed. After excluding negative and positive sentiments and only leave more specific emotions, then we have a better idea of the type of sentiments the literature is about. I noticed that fear and disgust were before âpositiveâ sentiments which was misleading. In my opinion, sentiments are more abstract rather than factual, so sentiments in this case are not appropiate for scientific literature.

  1. Now perform a sentiment analysis using the AFINN lexicon to get an average positivity score for each abstract (hint: you may want to create a variable that indexes, or counts, the abstracts). Create a visualization that shows these scores grouped by search term. Are any search terms noticeably different from the others?
afinn <- get_sentiments("afinn") 
afinn_means <- pubmed %>%
  mutate(abstract_id = row_number()) %>%
  unnest_tokens(word, abstract) %>%
  inner_join(afinn, by = "word") %>%
  group_by(term, abstract_id) %>%
  summarise(mean_score = mean(value), .groups = "drop") %>%
  right_join(pubmed %>% mutate(abstract_id = row_number()) %>% select(term, abstract_id), by = c("term","abstract_id")) %>%
  mutate(mean_score = replace_na(mean_score, 0))

ggplot(afinn_means,
       aes(x = fct_reorder(term, mean_score, .fun = mean, .desc = TRUE),
           y = mean_score)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(x = "Term", y = "AFINN mean score per abstract",
       title = "Average AFINN positivity score per abstract by term")

I noticed that cystic fibrosis is the only term with an average positive AFINN score while prostate cancer was the most negative.
